meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Brewes","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): habitational name from Briouze in Orne.","(Northumberland and Durham): topographic name or nickname from Middle English <i>breuhous</i> ‘brewery’ (literally ‘brew house’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bruce","meanings":["Scottish (of Norman origin): habitational name from a place in Normandy, probably from Brix (La Manche).","Altered form of French   Brousse  .","History: The son of the Domesday baron, a friend of David I of Scotland, was granted by him the Lordship of Annandale in 1124, and his second son Robert became the founder of the Scottish house of Bruce. — This surname (see 2 above) is listed along with its original form <i>Brousse</i> in the (US) National Huguenot Society's register of qualified Huguenot ancestors."]}]},{"name":"Lucy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From Old French <i>Lucie</i>, the vernacular form of   Lucia .  It is sometimes assumed that <i>Lucy</i> is a pet form of   Lucinda  , but there is no etymological justification for this assumption. It was in fairly widespread use in the Middle Ages, and increased greatly in popularity in the 18th century and again in the 1990s. In Ireland it serves as an Anglicized form of Irish Luíseach ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705191,"age":21,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":34,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":43,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","julianDay":2209390,"title":"The Hundred Years' War","description":"The Hundred Years' War between France and England was largely due to the question of legitimate succession to the French crown.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705195,"age":88,"year":"1382","julianDay":2225826,"title":"Wycliffe's Bible","description":"John Wycliffe, English theologian and professor at the University of Oxford, completed a translation of the Bible from the Latin Vulgate into Middle English. This translation is known as Wycliffe's Bible and was completed around 1382.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wycliffe%27s_Bible","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Wycliffe's Bible","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"When Lucy de Brewes was born on 17 May 1293, in Buckingham, Buckinghamshire, England, her father, Giles de Braose, was 25 and her mother, Beatrice de St Helena, was 22. She married Robert de Mautravers about 1309, in Bramber, Sussex, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son. She died in Crowell, Oxfordshire, England."},"et":{"17 May 1293–":"17. mai 1293–Surnud","1293–Female":"1293–Surnud","1292–1321":"1292–1321","–1354":"–1354","1310–1353":"1310–135